Steps to install:

1. $ git clone --recursive git@github.com:jyrikimari/mlkmc.git
2. On desktop:
   $ make

   should be sufficient. The QUIP library will be built as
   a part of compilation, and you will be prompted to make
   choices in QUIP's make config. The default option should
   work for everything EXCEPT
   "Would you like to compile with GAP support ? [y/n]"
   Here you should choose y instead of the default n.

   The way LAMMPS is linked requires setting
   $ export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/path/to/mlkmc/lammps/src:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH
   before running, both on desktop and on clusters.

   On clusters, you will need to load the appropriate modules
   and build the appropriate target. Support currently extends
   to the CSC Puhti cluster, the NSC Tetralith cluster,
   and the Helsinki University Turso cluster federation.

   When QUIP's make config prompts you to choose
   "Would you like to compile with preconditioned minimisation support? (not working with Intel compiler) [y/n]",
   it is most likely wise to choose n if you are using Intel
   compiler, as instructed here for Puhti and Tetralith.

   On Puhti:
   $ module load intel-oneapi-compilers intel-oneapi-mpi intel-oneapi-mkl
   $ make puhti

   On Tetralith:
   $ module load buildenv-intel/2023a-eb
   $ make tetralith

   On Turso:
   $ module load OpenMPI OpenBLAS LAPACK
   $ make turso

Running on desktop (mainly for testing/developing):

   You need an in.mlkmc file in the working directory (example
   provided), and a LAMMPS style interatomic potential energy
   function in the place indicated in in.mlkmc. Then, if
   the mlkmc directory have been added to your PATH, to run:
   $ mpirun -n 11 --oversubscribe mlkmc

   The number of MPI tasks, here 11, is equal to the default number
   of NEB replicas in the barrier calculations. If you change
   the parameter neb_images in in.mlkmc, change the number of
   mpirun -n parameter accordingly. On a desktop, you most likely
   need the --oversubscribe flag to have enough "cores" available.

   On a desktop, you may want to direct stdout to a file, by e.g.
   $ mpirun -n 11 --oversubscribe mlkmc | tee mlkmc.out

Running on clusters:

   In the sbatch script, set -N 1, --ntasks-per-node=11 and --cpus-per-task=1.
   Then (again if mlkmc can be found in your PATH), include the following commands
   in the script, depending on the platform.

   On Puhti:
   module load intel-oneapi-compilers intel-oneapi-mpi intel-oneapi-mkl
   ulimit -Ss unlimited
   srun mlkmc

   On Tetralith:
   module load buildenv-intel/2023a-eb
   ulimit -Ss unlimited
   srun mlkmc

   On Turso:
   module load OpenMPI OpenBLAS LAPACK
   srun --mpi=pmix mlkmc
